      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the slow-moving principal on your student loan statement is a common experience, and it's not unlike the way a slow-moving, stubborn old gnome might be. When you make your full payments, you're essentially throwing a bunch of gold coins at the gnome, but he only takes a few at a time and keeps the rest for himself. The interest on your loan is like the gnome's hidden stash of gold coins, and it's calculated based on the remaining balance of your loan. Each month, the gnome takes a little more of your gold coins (interest) and adds it to his stash, which is why the principal balance doesn't seem to move much at first. But don't worry, as you keep making your full payments, the gnome will eventually have to part with more of his stash, and your principal balance will start to decrease faster. Just remember, patience is key when dealing with these slow-moving gnomes.",
